<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Founder of Pit-track K9 conservation and anti-poaching unit Carl Thornton, said they were alerted to the lion's presence at the beginning of August when someone allegedly drove into it. Thornton said they Together with Drew Abrahamson from the Captured in Africa Foundation, have been working to save the lion's life. "Lion footprints were positively identified at the scene of the accident and a nearby killing of a cow calf was also identified," said Thornton.Thornton said the lion was again identified when a farmer spotted it on his CCTV cameras at night. Following that, footprints and killings were once again spotted in the vicinity of the area where the lion was identified on CCTV cameras. "We now believe that we know the area the lion is located and believe we will be able to capture him," said Thornton.A piece of meat will be drag over a large area today to create a trail to lead the lion to a specific area.Once there, a piece of beaten meat with a sedative in it will be waiting for him. After the lion has eaten the meat, he will be darted and taken to the Pretoria Zoo. "The reason why we sedate him with the meat first is because we are afraid he will run away when we dart him and we might lose his location once again.When he's sedated, he will be disorientated and hence not be able to run far," said Thornton. The lion will most likely be captured during the night when he is most active.So far, a second home to the lion has been arranged with Pretoria Zoo before a more suitable facility is found.